The sudden onset of lower back pain radiating down the leg, along with positive straight leg raise test, suggests the most likely diagnosis is a disc herniation. Osteomyelitis would have more systemic symptoms, such as fever, and would likely involve more than just the lower back. Spinal stenosis typically presents with a gradual onset of symptoms, and ankylosing spondylitis is characterized by stiffness and limited mobility.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The sudden onset of lower back pain and radiation of pain down the leg with a straight leg raise suggests disc herniation. Osteomyelitis usually presents with localized pain and tenderness, fever, and leukocytosis. Spinal stenosis presents with neurogenic claudication and numbness/tingling in the bilateral lower extremities. Ankylosing spondylitis presents with stiffness in the lower back and hip joints, usually in young males. The intact sensation to light touch and pin-prick helps rule out any nerve damage.
